<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n18128e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n18" href="#n18128e">N18 (VI.B.8)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n18all.htm#n18128e"> 128(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Abraham Tripier</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It was further ordered &ldquo;that all such of the said persecuted Protestants as shall within five years from the date hereof make their application for their freedoms here, and are artisans and handicraftsmen, shall be admitted to the freedom of this city without fines or fees, and also, for the space of five years to come from the date hereof, shall be freed of all city taxes.&rdquo; As a consequence of this Order we find that there were several French Protestants admitted to the franchise of the city in January, 1682. Amongst the names of those admitted occurs that of <mark>Abraham Tripier</mark>, &ldquo;silk weaver.&rdquo; <small> J. J. Webb, <a name="WSID" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WSID"><cite title="source">The Silk Industry in Ireland</cite></a> (1913) 128</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Cf. <a name="sh8010k" href="sh8all.htm#sh8010k">Sheet viii-10(k)</a>, from VI.C.7 transcription. First silk weaver mentioned in the municipal records of Dublin.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c07086a" href="c7all.htm#c07086a">VI.C.07:086(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
